First, let us learn 27 nakshatras in the Zodiac.

As I mentioned in chapter two, Zodiac is the area of the sky that extends nine degrees north or south of the ecliptic plane.

So the Zodiac has no start Or end Point.

We use stars(Nakshatras) to mark the starting and end point of the zodiac.

For example, the nakshatra Ashwini is the starting point of the Zodiac belt, whereas the Nakshatra Revati is the endpoint of the Zodiac belt.

Let us go through the 27 Nakshatras in the Zodiac.

Of course, as an astrologer, you need to remember these 27 Nakshatras

If you read these nakshatra several times in a day You can easily remember these Nakshatras

Now let us do a bit of maths to find how these 27 Nakshatras are evenly distributed in 12 zodiac signs ie; 12 Rashis

We know that the Zodiac is 360 degree belt. We just learnt there are 27 Nakshatras in this zodiac.

To find the length of one Nakshatra We should divide 360 by 27.

So we would get 13 degrees, 20 minutes as the length of one Nakshatra

We already learnt that there are 12 signs or rashis.

To find the length of one Rashi We should divide 360 by 12. So the length of one Rashi is 30 degree.

Now one nakshatra has four padas. So we just calculated that the length of one Nakshatra is 13 degrees 20 minutes.

So, therefore the length of one pada is 3 degrees, 20 minutes(ie; 13 degrees 20 minutes divided by 4 = 3 degrees 20 minutes)

Let me repeat the length of one Nakshatra is 13 degrees, 20 minutes.

The length of one Rashi is 30 degrees.

Each Nakshatra has four padas

So the length of one nakshatra pada is 3 degrees, 20 minutes.

These 27 Nakshatras are evenly distributed in 12 Rashis

So in order to find how many Nakshatras can fit into one Rashi, we should divide the length of the Rashi by the length of nakshatra.

So the length of Rashi is 30 degrees. The length of one Nakshatra is 13 degrees. If you divide 30 by 13, you will get 2.25, that is two full Nakshatras + quarter Nakshatra

Or in other words, 2 full Nakshatras has eight padas because one Nakshatra has

words, 2 full Nakshatras has eight padas because one Nakshatra has 4 padas so for two full Nakshatras will have eight padas.

Therefore, we can conclude that one Rashi will contain nine Nakshatra padas

So let me summarize. One Rashi can hold only nine nakshatra padas.

So whatever Nakshatra pada that are left over will be added to the next Rashi

For example, one Rashi can hold nine Nakshatra padas with two full Nakshatra ie; 4+4

And Quarter of one Nakshatra(1/4 of Nakshatra) which is one pada

Or one Rashi can hold 3/4 of one Nakshatra which is 3 padas, and One full Nakshatra And half of another Nakshatra which is 2 pada.

So what will happen to the next Rashi? This remaining will add first, which is 2 padas one Nakshatra and one full Nakshatra which is 4 pada

and another 3/4 another Nakshatra which adds up to nine pada. 

So this is how all the Nakshatras are evenly distributed in 12 Rashis

Now, with this table, you can easily understand how Nakshatras are evenly distributed in 12 Rashis.

First, the Aries(Mesha) has 4 padas of Ashwini, 4 padas of Bharani and 1 pada of Kritika. The Aries ends at 30 degrees. 

So the Taurus(Vrishabha or Rishabha) has 2nd, 3rd and 4th padas of Kritika and 4 Padas of the Rohini, and 1st & 2nd pada of Mrigashira. The sign Taurus ends at 60 degrees.

The sign Gemini(Mithuna) has 3rd & 4th pada of Mrigashira, 4 padas of Ardra and 1st, 2nd & 3rd pada of Punarvasu. The sign Gemini ends at 90 degrees.

The sign cancer(Kataka or Karkataka) has 4th pada of punarvasu, 4 padas of Pushya and 4 padas of Ashlesha. So the sign cancer ends at 120 degrees.

The sign Leo(Simha or Sima) has 4 padas of Magha, 4 padas of Poorva-Falguni and 1st pada of Uttara-Falguni. The sign Leo ends at 150

1st pada of Uttara-Falguni. The sign Leo ends at 150 degrees.

The sign Virgo(Kanya) has 2nd, 3rd & 4th padas of Uttar-Falguni, 4 padas of Hasta, and 1st & 2nd padas of Chitra. The Virgo ends at 180 degrees.

The sign Libra(Thula) has 3rd & 4th padas of Chitra, 4 padas of Swati and 1st, 2nd & 3rd padas of Vishaka. The sign Libra ends at 210 degrees.

The sign Scorpio(Vrishika) has 4th pada of Vishakha, 4 padas of Anuradha and 4 padas of Jyestha. The Scorpio ends at 240 degrees.

The sign Sagittarius(Dhanus) has 4 padas of Moola, 4 padas of Poorva-Shadha and 1st pada of Uttar-Shadha. The Sagittarius ends at 270 degrees.

The sign Capricorn(Makara) has 2nd, 3rd & 4th padas of Uttar-Shadha, 4 padas of Shravana, and 1st & 2nd padas of Dhanishtha. The Capricorn ends at 300 degrees.

The sign Aquarius(Kumbha) has 3rd & 4th padas of Dhanishtha, 4 padas of Shatbhisha, and 1st, 2nd & 3rd padas of Poorva-Bhadrapada. The sign Aquarius ends at 330 degrees.

The sign Pisces(Meena) has 4th pada of Poorva-Bhadrapada, 4 padas of Uttara-Bhadrapada and 4 padas of Revati. Thus the sign Pisces ends at 360 degrees Completing the entire zodiac.

Once you remember the Nakshatra names, you can easily build this chart Just by allocating nine padas for each Rashis.
